1
00:00:01,000 --> 00:00:06,500
Job hunting means the same work over and over.
Finding the postings. Reading them properly.

2
00:00:06,500 --> 00:00:11,500
Working out whether you're actually a fit.
DevJobInfo does that part for you.

3
00:00:13,000 --> 00:00:16,500
Everything lands on one dashboard.

4
00:00:17,000 --> 00:00:24,000
How many jobs came in, how well they match you,
and how many applications you've sent this week.

5
00:00:25,000 --> 00:00:30,500
Underneath, your pipeline by stage — saved, applied,
interviewing, and the ones that have gone quiet.

6
00:00:31,000 --> 00:00:38,500
Plus how your match scores are spread, so you can see
whether you're aiming at the right roles.

7
00:00:39,000 --> 00:00:44,000
It all rests on your profile.
This is what every job gets scored against.

8
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:51,000
Drop in your CV and it fills itself in —
skills, experience, education, the lot.

9
00:00:52,000 --> 00:00:58,500
From there you can adjust anything. The more accurate
this is, the more honest the scoring gets.

10
00:01:03,000 --> 00:01:09,000
Search five job boards at once —
one query instead of five tabs.

11
00:01:11,000 --> 00:01:16,000
Or paste a URL straight in, and it'll pull
the posting apart for you.

12
00:01:17,000 --> 00:01:25,000
Postings in any language work as they are. A Danish job
stays in Danish — nothing gets translated behind your back.

13
00:01:27,000 --> 00:01:32,000
Every job comes back scored from nought to a hundred
against your profile.

14
00:01:33,000 --> 00:01:39,800
When a posting is too thin to judge fairly, it caps
the score instead of pretending otherwise.

15
00:01:40,000 --> 00:01:43,500
Open any job for the full reasoning.

16
00:01:44,000 --> 00:01:48,800
Which skills matched, which are missing,
and why it landed there.

17
00:01:49,200 --> 00:01:54,500
Experience and seniority score separately, so a skills
match can't mask a role that's too junior.

18
00:01:55,000 --> 00:02:00,000
From here, a cover letter —
written from your actual history.

19
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:07,000
In the language of the posting,
so a Danish job gets a Danish letter.

20
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:19,500
And nothing invented. No companies you didn't work for,
no projects you didn't build. Only what's in your profile.

21
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:29,000
Then a resume tailored to this specific role.

22
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:38,000
Same career, reordered around what this employer actually
asked for — the relevant work first, the rest still there.

23
00:02:42,000 --> 00:02:46,000
Both download as PDFs, ready to send.

24
00:02:55,000 --> 00:02:58,000
Find the jobs. Research the companies. Land the role.

25
00:02:58,500 --> 00:03:00,100
DevJobInfo — devjob.info
